  "prompt": "Why are smart people not always rich?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why intelligence doesn't necessarily translate to financial success:\n\n1. Different types of intelligence\n- Academic intelligence doesn't always equal financial intelligence\n- Emotional intelligence and practical skills are also important\n\n2. Career choices\n- Some highly intelligent people choose lower-paying fields like research or education\n- Passion for work may outweigh financial considerations\n\n3. Financial literacy\n- Intelligence doesn't guarantee understanding of money management\n- Skills like investing, budgeting, and financial planning are separate from general intelligence\n\n4. Risk tolerance\n- Smart people might be more risk-averse\n- Entrepreneurs often take calculated risks to build wealth\n\n5. Motivation and work ethic\n- Intelligence alone isn't enough; consistent effort is crucial\n- Perseverance and hard work are key to financial success\n\n6. Opportunity and networking\n- Connections and opportunities play a significant role in wealth creation\n- Not all intelligent people have access to the same networks\n\n7. Personal values\n- Some prioritize personal fulfillment over financial gain\n- Altruistic pursuits might not lead to high income\n\n8. Economic and social barriers\n- Systemic inequalities can limit wealth accumulation\n- Background and circumstances impact financial opportunities\n\nIntelligence is just one factor among many that contribute to financial success.",
